-- ── Expensify ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Expensify is a cloud-based expense management platform that combines receipt-scanning software with a corporate card, travel booking and bill pay, letting businesses automate expense reports, approvals and reimbursements from a single app.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium / Subscription (per active member)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free for individuals; Collect plan starts at $5 per member per month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2008, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$51-200 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Portland, Oregon, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Expensify Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Expensify review 2026: SmartScan receipts, the Expensify Card, Travel and Bill Pay. See real Collect and Control pricing, features, pros, cons and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Expensify is a cloud-based expense management and corporate spend platform built around automated receipt scanning, expense report creation, approval workflows and reimbursement. The company was founded in 2008 by David Barrett, who first pitched the concept at TechCrunch50 as 'Expensify: The Corporate Card for the Masses,' framing it as a way to simplify the tedious, manual process of tracking business receipts and filing expense reports. Barrett, a University of Michigan graduate and serial entrepreneur who had previously worked on peer-to-peer technology at Red Swoosh, built the company's early technology around one core insight: expense reporting was broken because it forced employees to manually re-type data from paper receipts. Expensify's response was SmartScan, one of the first receipt-scanning technologies in the expense management industry, which uses optical character recognition (OCR) and machine learning to extract merchant, date, amount and category data from a photographed receipt and automatically populate an expense line item. The company is headquartered in Portland, Oregon, in the historic former First National Bank Building, and has maintained a significant presence in Michigan as well, reflecting Barrett's roots and an early partnership with Gogebic Community College to expand technical operations outside the West Coast.

Expensify grew through a series of early venture funding rounds, raising roughly 1 million dollars in 2009, 5.7 million dollars in 2010, and additional capital in 2014 and 2015, with the 2015 round coinciding with the launch of Expensify Ventures, an internal fund. Over the following decade the company expanded well beyond receipt scanning into a full spend-management suite. In November 2021, Expensify went public on the Nasdaq Global Select Market under the ticker symbol EXFY, pricing its initial public offering at 27 dollars per share and raising net proceeds of roughly 57.5 million dollars after underwriting costs, with joint bookrunners J.P. Morgan Securities, Citigroup Global Markets and BofA Securities. The IPO valued the company at approximately 3.87 billion dollars at debut. Since going public, Expensify has published its financials as a listed company; for the 2022 fiscal year it reported revenue of about 169 million dollars alongside a net loss of roughly 27 million dollars, and its stock price has fallen sharply from IPO levels, reflecting broader pressure on expense-management valuations amid growing competition from newer, card-led spend platforms.

Technically, Expensify operates as a workflow engine layered on top of receipt capture. Employees submit expenses by photographing a paper receipt with the mobile app, forwarding an emailed receipt to a dedicated Expensify inbox, or connecting a bank or credit card feed so that transactions import automatically. SmartScan then extracts the relevant fields, applies the company's expense policy rules (per diem limits, category restrictions, required fields) and flags violations before a report is ever submitted, which reduces back-and-forth between employees and finance teams. Approved reports route through configurable, multi-level approval workflows and can be reimbursed directly through Expensify's integrated payment rails, typically arriving in an employee's bank account within one to two business days for domestic transfers. The platform integrates with major accounting and ERP systems including QuickBooks Online and Desktop, Xero, NetSuite, Sage Intacct and FinancialForce, syncing chart-of-accounts data, tax codes and vendor records so that finance teams do not have to re-key transactions. On top of the core expense-report engine, Expensify has layered three additional products: the Expensify Card, a corporate charge card that offers cash-back rewards (1 percent standard, up to 2 percent at very high spend volumes) and lets administrators set category-level spending controls and freeze cards instantly from the app; Expensify Travel, a built-in booking tool for flights, hotels, cars and rail that in 2026 added consolidated travel billing so companies can pay for all employee travel on a single monthly statement rather than issuing cards to every traveler; and Bill Pay, which extends the same approval and payment infrastructure to vendor invoices and accounts payable.

Expensify's pricing structure separates individual use from company workspaces. Individuals can use Expensify for free, with up to 25 SmartScans per month, unlimited manual expense entry, distance tracking and CSV or spreadsheet export, making it suitable for freelancers and sole proprietors who need basic receipt capture without collaboration features. For teams, the company restructured its pricing in April 2025 to simplify what had become a complicated set of discount tiers and commitments. The Collect plan now costs a flat 5 dollars per member per month with no annual contract required, and is aimed at small businesses that need basic approval and reimbursement structure without deep integrations. The Control plan, aimed at larger or more compliance-sensitive organizations, adds multi-level approvals, ERP integrations, HR and payroll connections, multiple corporate card connections, custom expense rules and SAML/SSO; it is priced at 9 dollars per active member per month with an annual commitment when paired with the Expensify Card, 18 dollars per member per month annually without the card, or 36 dollars per member per month on a pay-per-use, no-commitment basis. In both team plans, 'active member' generally means a user who creates, submits, approves, reimburses or exports a report in a given billing period, rather than every seat provisioned.

Expensify's target audience spans a wide range of company sizes, from solo freelancers and small businesses on the free or Collect tiers up to mid-market and larger companies that need Control's compliance and integration depth. Its most direct competitors include SAP Concur, a legacy enterprise incumbent known for deep ERP and travel-policy integration but criticized for a complex interface, per-transaction pricing and slow innovation; Ramp and Brex, newer card-led spend management platforms that bundle corporate cards, bill pay and expense automation with often more aggressive free tiers and automation-focused positioning; and smaller point solutions like Zoho Expense and Rydoo. Within this landscape Expensify differentiates itself through its long history and brand recognition as the pioneer of automated receipt scanning, its simplicity relative to Concur, and its willingness to offer a genuinely free individual tier, though it has faced increasing competitive pressure from card-issuing challengers that can subsidize software costs through interchange revenue. Notable events in the company's history include a 2017 privacy incident in which some Expensify receipt images were found to have been reviewed by human contractors through Amazon's Mechanical Turk service for data-verification purposes, which drew public scrutiny of the company's data-handling practices, as well as community and civic initiatives such as funding the renovation of a Portland food-cart pod. As of the most recent public disclosures, Expensify employed roughly 130 to 140 people, a comparatively lean headcount for a publicly traded software company serving a large global customer base, reflecting the company's historical emphasis on automation and self-serve adoption over a large direct sales organization.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '22ab0c21-f5e6-4e9a-919f-4e80fdc79abb';

